{"product_id": "15100", "page": 57, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2016-12-26", "text": "The first Assassins Creed is a damn fine game and one of the first things that truly got me interested in history. I find the story and the setting to be most intriguing and honestly I would recommend the game on those two merits alone.\n\nProgression of skill is something in this game I remember well and it really bothers me that they did away with that in the later entries. In this game there is a true sense of progression of skill as you go through your missions, learning new ways to fight and perfecting your movement.\n\nWhen I first started playing I hardly knew how to move around or use my sword properly but by the end it became easier and more fluid purely through practice and earned skill.\n\nAnd that's something I really miss.", "hours": 17.9, "username": "Danny Rodriguez", "products": 190, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "15100", "page": 57, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2016-12-26", "text": "First Game in the series. The trilogy is my favorite of all AC games from the story. Too bad they discontinued it.", "hours": 28.8, "username": "digibluez", "products": 583, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "15100", "page": 57, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2016-12-26", "text": "Almost 10 years old but looks really good. Nice gameplay and interesting system. And I heard that second part is far better...For xbox pad go and find patch - then controls are smooth and intuitive.", "hours": 2.3, "user_id": "76561198127786620", "username": "caspro", "products": 19, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "15100", "page": 57, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2016-12-25", "text": "First instalment of the series, baby steps.\nThe game itself is still nice to play even today, it seems the graphics have been made universal and are not that bad.\nGameplay, every action is like an animation, until it's finished, nothing else can be done. This is also noticable when jumping the roofs, loads of falling into the streets.\nThe Storyline is what captures the most in my opinion. Although it is attempted to recreate historical places and characters, I would probably guess most of the stuff is still fictional.\nLets talk numbers. 9 bosses, 9 zones. Each zone: 8 citizens to save, 8 viewpoints to see, 6 side missions to unlock information: 1 pickpocket, 1 eavesdropping, 1 beatup, 1 assassinations, 1 flags collection, 1 roof parkout. You must do 2-3 side missions to unlock boss fight. After 3rd boss this is getting into a repetitive chore. Although there is increase in guards/npcs, it is still repetitive.\nOverall the game is nice, minimum bugs, good game play, still good time sink.\nBig thumbs up for no Uplay stuff yet, good things of an old title.\nDo recommend.", "hours": 20.6, "username": "Rossos", "products": 1294, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "15100", "page": 57, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2016-12-25", "text": "after buying this game i want register it with uplay or ubisoft and doing the register process i cant see any game added to my uplay library although i dont receive any emails or something from ubisoft.", "hours": 4.7, "username": "Abelz", "products": 35, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "15100", "page": 57, "page_order": 8, "recommended": false, "date": "2016-12-24", "text": "The controls are terrible. You fight the camera just as much as enemy soldiers. You go to the towns and do the SAME quests and side quests throughought the whole game with no variation, and there were several times where the game forces you into combat when all you want to do is run away. The game is just 12 hours of \u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665ing boring.", "hours": 18.0, "username": "Grizzly Fate", "products": 272, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
